{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492750"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:44:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1149"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1149"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.06,0.08,0.79]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109889"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92250"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"279"},{"type":"tags","id":"426"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"12902"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43977"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109889"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents with acute onset of visual blurring and painful eye movements in all directions in her left eye. This is her first episode. She denies any history of trauma. She describes \u0022flickering\u0022 in her peripheral visual field. She denies headache, neck pain, or speech disturbance. She reports associated weakness in both her legs, which she first noticed two days ago after a hot shower. She denies any bladder or bowel symptoms. She has no past medical history and has no family history of eye disease. She takes the oral contraceptive pill. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, extra-ocular eye movements are normal with no diplopia - however she does have pain on performing these movements. The pupils are equal and reactive, however you notice when moving the torch from right to left eye - the pupils appear more dilated than previously. A fundoscopic examination demonstrates optic disc swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute close angle glaucoma","Retinal detachment","Central retinal vein thrombosis","Cerebral sinus thrombosis","Optic neuritis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E. The examination involving the pupils is describing relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD) a sign of optic neuritis. This is likely a first presentation of a demyelinating disorder with the presence of leg weakness and Uhthoff\u0027s phenomenon described as a transient worsening of symptoms with raised body temperature. The diagnosis of multiple sclerosis should be made with McDonald criteria with evidence of dissemination of lesions in space and time. A MRI with gadolinium contrast may show white matter plaques.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute close angle glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E tends to affect the elderly or those with family history or personal history of eye disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal detachment\u003C/strong\u003E presents with floaters and flashes of light in their vision, followed by progressive visual field loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral retinal vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E affects the elderly, presenting with painless blurred vision and showing the characteristic \u0027blood and thunder\u0027 appearance of dilated and tortuous veins on fundoscopic examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with headache, intracranial hypertension, and possible seizures, encephalopathy, focal limb signs, and symptoms affecting cranial nerves 3, 4, 5 and 6.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Optic neuritis presents with eye pain, difficulty distinguishing colour and blurry vision.","Those presenting with optic neuritis have a 50% risk of going on to develop MS. (Optic neuritis study group, 2008)"],"references":["Toosy AT, Mason DF, Miller DH. Optic neuritis. Lancet Neurol. 2014 Jan;13(1):83-99. doi: 10.1016/S1474-4422(13)70259-X. PMID: 24331795.","RACGP, Multiple Sclerosis - diagnosis, management and prognosis. Australian family Physician, Neurology, December 2011. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/download/documents/AFP/2011/December/201112tsang.pdf","The Optic Neuritis Study Group. Multiple sclerosis risk after optic neuritis. Final Optic Neuritis Treatment Trial follow-up. Arch Neurol 2008;65:727\u201332."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92250"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1149"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92250"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T13:59:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T13:59:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item"